# 3. ITERATORS — THE HEART OF STL

This is one of the deepest STL concepts.

---

# SIMPLE DEFINITION

An iterator is:

# an object that points to elements inside containers

---

# VERY IMPORTANT IDEA

Iterators are generalized pointers.

---

# VISUAL IDEA

```text id="r4m8tb"
Iterator → points to data
```

---

# WHY ITERATORS EXIST

Different containers:

* vector
* set
* map
* list

have different internal structures.

Iterators provide:

# uniform traversal interface

---

# VECTOR ITERATOR

```cpp id="u7x1qc"
vector<int>::iterator it;
```

---

# BEGINNING ITERATOR

```cpp id="v3m9tb"
it = v.begin();
```

---

# END ITERATOR

```cpp id="x8v4wc"
v.end()
```

Points:

```text id="q5m2tb"
AFTER last element
```

Very important.

---

# ITERATOR TRAVERSAL

```cpp id="t7x4qc"
for(auto it = v.begin(); it != v.end(); it++) {

    cout << *it;
}
```

---

# BREAKING THIS DOWN

---

# `it`

Iterator variable.

---

# `v.begin()`

Iterator to first element.

---

# `v.end()`

Iterator after last element.

---

# `*it`

Dereference iterator.
Gets actual value.

---

# `it++`

Move iterator forward.

---

# WHY ITERATORS ARE DEEP

STL algorithms work using iterators.

Example:

```cpp id="m1v8tb"
sort(v.begin(), v.end());
```

Sort doesn't care:
whether data comes from:

* vector
* deque
* array

Iterators abstract traversal.

---

# ITERATORS INTERNALLY

For vectors:
iterators are often:

# raw pointers internally

For trees/maps:
more complex structures.

---

# 4. AUTO KEYWORD — TYPE INFERENCE

One of modern C++'s most useful features.

---

# SIMPLE IDEA

Compiler automatically deduces type.

---

# EXAMPLE

```cpp id="r6m3wc"
auto x = 10;
```

Compiler infers:

```text id="u2x9tb"
int
```

---

# WHY AUTO EXISTS

STL types can become extremely long.

---

# WITHOUT AUTO

```cpp id="x5m1qc"
vector<pair<int,string>>::iterator it;
```

---

# WITH AUTO

```cpp id="y8m4wc"
auto it = v.begin();
```

Much cleaner.

---

# WHY AUTO IS IMPORTANT

Modern professional C++ heavily uses:

# type inference

especially with:

* iterators
* lambdas
* templates

---

# AUTO DOES NOT MEAN DYNAMIC TYPING

Very important.

C++ remains:

# statically typed

Compiler infers type at compile time.

---

# VISUAL IDEA

```text id="q1v7tb"
Compiler figures type automatically
```

---

# 5. RANGE-BASED LOOPS

Modern C++ traversal syntax.

---

# OLD STYLE LOOP

```cpp id="u4m2qc"
for(int i = 0; i < v.size(); i++) {
    cout << v[i];
}
```

---

# RANGE-BASED LOOP

```cpp id="v9x5tb"
for(int x : v) {
    cout << x;
}
```

Cleaner and safer.

---

# HOW IT WORKS

Internally uses:

# iterators

---

# VISUAL IDEA

```text id="m2v8qc"
for each element in container
```

---

# IMPORTANT VARIANTS

---

# COPY VERSION

```cpp id="r7m1wc"
for(auto x : v)
```

Copies elements.

---

# REFERENCE VERSION

```cpp id="t4x6tb"
for(auto &x : v)
```

Directly accesses original elements.

---

# WHY REFERENCE IMPORTANT

Allows:

* modification
* avoids copying
* improves performance

---

# EXAMPLE

```cpp id="y1m9qc"
for(auto &x : v) {
    x *= 2;
}
```

Modifies original vector.

---

# CONST REFERENCE VERSION

```cpp id="u6x3tb"
for(const auto &x : v)
```

Best for:

* large objects
* read-only access

Professional style.

---

# HOW THESE 5 CONCEPTS CONNECT

---

# VECTOR

Stores data.

---

# PAIR

